habitat_description:
This species occurs in coastal oak woodlands found in northern California in Humboldt County and extend southward to Valle Santo Tomás, Baja California del Norte, Mexico (Green et al. 2013). Also found in islands of South Farallon, Santa Catalina, Los Coronados, and Año Nuevo (Lynch and Wake 1974; McPeak 2000). A genetically distinct population from the coast occurs in black oak and yellow pine forests in the foothills of the Sierra Nevada (Lynch and Wake 1974; Jackman 1993). Habitat is characterized by moist soil and distribution of this species follows the distribution of the oaks (Quercus agrifolia and Q. wislizenii), while in southern California the species is mostly associated with sycamores (Platanus racemosa) that border streams (Rosenthal 1957; Lanoo 2005).
This species is found in a wide variety of habitats including under rocks, logs, woody cover, decaying stumps, and rock crevices (Stebbins 1951; Lanoo 2005). Also, individuals are known to use trees and have been reported up to 18 meters above ground (Ritter 1903; Stebbins 1951). Early reports conclude that this species is absent in areas that do not receive more than 25 cm of annual precipitation (Rosenthal 1957). Primary threat to habitat of live oak is development (Green et al. 2013).
